In order to make all these scripts work, you need to add some
special sudo rules. These include:

8<---------------------------------------------------------------

# Allow kiosk updater to be called
ALL     ALL=NOPASSWD: /usr/sbin/argonaut-install-kiosk-profile ""

# Allow usbmanager to be called
ALL     ALL=NOPASSWD: /usr/sbin/argonaut-start-usb ""
ALL     ALL=NOPASSWD: /usr/sbin/argonaut-start-usb cleanup
ALL     ALL=NOPASSWD: /usr/sbin/argonaut-stop-usb ""
ALL     ALL=NOPASSWD: /usr/sbin/argonaut-printer-manager ""

# Connect network drives
ALL     ALL=NOPASSWD: /usr/sbin/argonaut-mount-shares ""
ALL     ALL=NOPASSWD: /usr/sbin/argonaut-umount-shares ""

# Profile sync
ALL     ALL=NOPASSWD: /usr/sbin/argonaut-profile-upload ""
ALL     ALL=NOPASSWD: /usr/sbin/argonaut-profile-download ""

# Allow last to be called
ALL     ALL=NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/last -R -n2 [a-z0-9_][a-z0-9_]*

8<---------------------------------------------------------------

If you have users which are administrators, you need these additional
settings to let them do a "sudo -s":

8<---------------------------------------------------------------

# Members of the admin group may gain root privileges
# (!) The shell is a workaround to make the above rules play
# (!) well, please do not replace /bin/bash with ALL!
root            ALL=(ALL) ALL
%admins         ALL=(ALL) /bin/bash

-----------------------------------------------------------------

This will allow "root" to do any things as usual (you cannot and
should not use this as a graphical login account), and ordinary
users inside of the group "admins" is allowed to do a "sudo -s" -
set that /bin/bash is your login shell.

